observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the City Mayor direct the OIC-City General Services Officer to:
 ensure the conduct of a complete annual physical count of PPE and the periodic reconciliation with the accounting records to facilitate timely verification and adjustment of the discrepancy between the accounting records and the RPCPPE, totaling P1,616,623,611.20;
 assign property number/tag to each PPE that will serve as an effective control on the use of government property and equipment;
 see to it that the RPCPPE was reviewed and verified before submission to the Audit Team; and
 submit the RPCPPE to the Audit Team later than January 31 of each year, in compliance with Section 124 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I.

We recommended that the City Mayor:
(a) require all personnel with outstanding cash advances to immediately settle their unliquidated cash advances. Henceforth, compel all employees granted with cash advances to liquidate the same as soon as the purposes for which these were given have been served;
(b) instruct the City Accountant that subsequent grant of cash advance is supported with certification that their previous cash advance was already liquidated and or proper accounting thereof is made;
(c) instruct the City Accountant to use the appropriate account for cash advances granted for official travel and operating expenses and make the necessary adjustment/s;
(d) require the concerned Accountable Officers to refund the unexpended balance of cash advances totaling P216,164.07; and
(e) impose the withholding of salary of accountable officers who failed to effect the prompt liquidation of their cash advances.

We recommended that the City Mayor:
(a) see to it that subsequent claims of honoraria should be equivalent based on the provisions prescribed by DBM Budget Circular No. 2004-5A;
(b) instruct the BAC Chairman to submit to the Audit Team the list of completed procurement projects with authenticated copy of the Notice of Award of each project as a reference for the actual claim of honorarium; otherwise a Notice of Suspension may be issued to ensure submission of the required documents;
(c) instruct the City Accountant to ensure that withholding taxes are deducted from payments made, in compliance with Section 2.79 of RR No. 10-2008, and remit the same to the BIR within the prescribed period; and
(d) direct the City Accountant to refrain from paying the honoraria to personnel assigned in the procuring unit of the City; they can avail of overtime subject to existing policies.

We recommended that the City Mayor:
(a) direct the Market Administrator to ensure that the contract of lease is signed by the City officials concerned and the qualified occupants; 
(b) direct the Market Administrator to prepare and submit a regular report on the actual occupants of the market stalls for monitoring purposes; 
(c) enjoin the Market Administrator and the City Treasurer to prepare and submit Monthly Report of Collections, and report on the uncollected dues of stallholders for monitoring and recording; and
(d) instruct the City Treasurer and the Market Administrator to maximize their efforts to realize targeted collection to attain efficiency and to generate additional income for the City.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the OIC-City General Services Officer to:
a) ensure the conduct of a complete annual physical count of PPE and the periodic reconciliation with the accounting records to facilitate timely verification and adjustment of the discrepancy totaling P1,318,579,831.25;
b) dispose of the unserviceable property at the soonest possible time to minimize the assets’ wear and tear or further deterioration;
c) draw Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to drop the semi-expendable property from the PPE accounts; and
d) provide depreciation for the City’s Road Networks.

We recommended that the City Mayor:
a) require all personnel with outstanding cash advances to immediately settle their unpaid balances. Henceforth, compel all employees granted with cash advances to liquidate the same as soon as the purposes for which these were given have been served;
b) discontinue the practice of granting additional cash advance to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance given him/her is liquidated and or proper accounting thereof is made;
c) direct the concerned accountable officers to refund the unexpended balance of cash advances totaling P184,797.54; and
d) strictly comply with the provisions of Section 89 of PD No. 1445, Items 5.1.1, 5.8, 5.9 and 8 of COA Circular No. 97-002 and if necessary, impose the corresponding penalty and sanctions against those officers with unliquidated cash advances, under Item 5.1.3 of the said COA Circular.

We recommended that the City Mayor:
a) direct the Market Administrator to ensure that the contract of lease is signed by the City officials concerned and the qualified stallholders;
b) direct the Market Administrator to prepare/submit a regular report on the actual occupants of the market stalls for monitoring purposes;
c) enjoin the Market Administrator and the City Treasurer to prepare and submit Monthly Report of Collections, and report on the uncollected dues of stallholders for monitoring and recording; and
d) direct the City Accountant to prepare the necessary audit adjusting journal entry for the unrecorded unpaid stall rental of P2,031,102.00 for the fair presentation of the affected accounts, and to prepare separate financial statements to account for and monitor the operations of the Public Market.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the:
1) Inventory Team to complete the physical inventory of all PPE;
2) City Accountant to coordinate with the City General Services Officer (GSO) to address reconciling discrepancies;
3) City GSO to submit the complete Inventory Reports to the Auditor not later than January 31 of each year;
4) Pamantasan ng Cabuyao (PnC) to use the required format in the physical count report shown in Appendix 49 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume II; and
5) City GSO to dispose the unserviceable properties at the soonest possible time to minimize the assets’ wear and tear or further deterioration.

We recommended that the City Mayor:
13) assign a Bottom-up Budgeting (BuB) Focal Person to make sure that the Local Poverty Reduction Action Team (LPRAT) will meet regularly to discuss and monitor the progress of each BuB project;
14) instruct the BuB Focal Person to review all the funds received by the City to facilitate the timely implementation of the planned programs and projects; 
15) submit all the documents related to the BuB projects to facilitate further evaluation of the Audit Team; and
16) instruct the City Treasurer to return the unexpended balance of P122,597.87 to the source agencies.
